PROBLEM TO POSE (turn ONLY this into the word problem; keep every number exactly as written):
- System: $\begin{cases} x + y = {{ linL[linear_eq_rhs] }} \\ {{ trigLhsL[trig_eq_lhs] }} = {{ trigRhsL[trig_eq_rhs] }} \end{cases}$
- Ask the student to find every pair (x, y) that satisfies this system.

=== INTERNAL (guidance for you only — never show, restate, paraphrase, number, or hint any of this to the student) ===
- Task: solve the system by SUBSTITUTION, using the sum-of-cosines formula.
- Method to recall:
  1) from the linear equation express y = {{ linL[linear_eq_rhs] }} - x;
  2) substitute into the second equation and apply the sum-to-product identity
     cos(x) + cos(y) = 2·cos((x + y)/2)·cos((x - y)/2) — note that BOTH arguments are
     divided by 2 (do not forget the halving);
  3) since x + y is already known to be {{ linL[linear_eq_rhs] }}, the factor
     cos((x + y)/2) is a CONSTANT (a table value) — this leaves a simplest equation in
     (x - y)/2; solve it for x;
  4) substitute the found x back into y = {{ linL[linear_eq_rhs] }} - x, carefully
     FLIPPING the signs when opening the bracket.
